  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Valid Anagram\n\nTwo strings are anagrams when they contain the same characters with the same frequencies. Given `s` and `t`, return whether `t` can be rearranged into `s`.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"listen\", t = \"silent\"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"binary\", t = \"brainy\"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"apple\", t = \"papelx\"\nOutput: false\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- `0 <= len(s), len(t) <= 50000`\n- `s` and `t` contain lowercase English letters.",
  "editorial": "Count the characters in both strings and compare the counts. Sorting also works, but counting keeps the runtime linear.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nfrom collections import Counter\n\nclass Solution:\n    def isAnagram(self, s, t):\n        return Counter(s) == Counter(t)\n```",
  "hints": [
    "If the lengths differ, the answer is immediately false.",
    "The order of characters does not matter; only counts matter."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def isAnagram(self, s, t):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "isAnagram"
  },
  "checker": {
    "type": "exact"
  },
  "time_limit_ms": 2000,
  "memory_limit_mb": 256,
